mit that a public notebook makes it harder to sell panic disguised as prudence. The Floodwalk sleeps easier, because tests feel like work and work quiets the teeth, and small wards begin humming the cadence as if to teach their own walls to listen. In the third night, you catch a faint answering hum from the sluice-veins that complicates every easy story, and Sula’s lamp remembers a storm-year that did not flood, only tightened belts. The Night Cartographers try to buy your raw notes with a mirror of the city none can find twice, but your refusal becomes its own small lantern, and strangers begin to nod to you in stairwells where they once watched you pass without a word.\"\n      ],\n      \"connections\": {\"previous\": [\"\"], \"next\": [\"M2\"]},\n      \"rewards\": [\n        {\"type\": \"Writ\", \"description\": \"Sealed Writ of Neutral Witness from the Protector, bearing the needle-and-river seal and granting access to civic hearings, guarded spaces, and council rooms where decisions are hammered while tempers glow.\"},\n        {\"type\": \"Access\", \"description\": \"Leave to traverse the Needle Keep’s sluice-galleries for future work, including bell-chain gantries and cold-forge passages, with a bell-token that hushes warders and unlocks iron grates.\"},\n        {\"type\": \"Item\", \"description\": \"A vial of memory oil from Lantern-keeper Sula tuned to storm-years, whose scent steadies the hand and clarifies recorded patterns when light wants to wander.\"}\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}"